Appendix B — Workload CTE: `new_type`, multischedule handling, and recording-time logic
B.1 What is `new_type` and how is it calculated?
In the workload CTE, `new_type` is a per-URL indicator showing whether a URL has any LIVE sessions associated with it. It is computed by grouping over URL and summing a LIVE flag:
    new_type = SUM(CASE WHEN lecturetype = 'LIVE' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)  -- grouped by URL
Helper CTE `b` retains only URLs where new_type = 0 (purely recorded URLs).
B.2 Why do we use `new_type`?
We use `new_type` to assign the correct event time for downstream aggregation:
• If `new_type = 0` (recorded-only), we take `createdat` from `user_experience.gold_videos` as the authoritative timestamp.
• Otherwise (LIVE present), we take `lecture_starttime` from `mview.gold_dbt_lecture_batch_info`.
This avoids misclassifying 'work done' based on batch upload date — especially important because 10–15 recorded lectures may be uploaded in bulk on a single day, which does not reflect when the work was actually performed.
B.3 Handling multischedule (faculty lecturing across multiple batches concurrently)
A faculty member may deliver the same session across 4–5 batches using the same URL. To prevent double counting, we deduplicate at the teacher × URL level using a window rank (`rnk`) and keep only the primary row:
    rnk = CASE WHEN ismultischedule = FALSE THEN 1
               ELSE ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
                      PARTITION BY teacher_id, main_url
                      ORDER BY CASE WHEN lecturetype = 'LIVE' THEN 1 ELSE 2 END,
                               conduct_date
                    )
          END
We then filter to `rnk = 1`. This prioritizes LIVE over recorded and then the earliest conduct_date, yielding a single canonical record per teacher × URL.
B.4 Deriving `conduct_date` (actual work date)
`conduct_date` represents the true day the lecture was delivered or recorded:
    conduct_date = CASE WHEN new_type = 0 THEN createdat  -- from user_experience.gold_videos
                        ELSE lecture_starttime            -- from mview.gold_dbt_lecture_batch_info
                   END
For recorded sessions, using the recording time captures the real work day, not the later upload time into the batch.
